---
// index.astro — Palestinians are Your Eyes | Anqa Theater
import "../styles/global.css";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import myImage from "../assets/anQa-03.png";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, viewport-fit=cover"
    />
    <title>Palestinians are Your Eyes | Anqa Theater</title>
    <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="../../public/anQa.svg" />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Playfair+Display:ital,wght@0,700;0,900;1,400;1,700&family=Source+Serif+4:opsz,wght@8..60,300;8..60,400;8..60,500&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Cormorant+Garamond:ital,wght@0,500;0,600;1,400;1,600&family=Playfair+Display:ital,wght@0,700;0,900;1,400;1,700&family=Source+Serif+4:opsz,wght@8..60,300;8..60,400;8..60,500&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />

    <!-- i18next -->
    <script src="https://unpkg.com/i18next@23.10.0/dist/umd/i18next.min.js"
    ></script>
    <script
      src="https://unpkg.com/i18next-browser-languagedetector@7.2.0/dist/umd/i18nextBrowserLanguageDetector.min.js"
    ></script>
  </head>

  <body>
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="site-header">
        <div class="logo-area">
          <Image src={myImage} alt="Anqa Theater Logo" class="logo-image" />
        </div>
        <div class="lang-area">
          <button
            class="globe-btn"
            id="globeButton"
            aria-label="Change language"
          >
            <svg
              class="globe-icon"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
            >
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
              <path
                d="M2 12H22M12 2C9.5 4.5 8 8 8 12C8 16 9.5 19.5 12 22C14.5 19.5 16 16 16 12C16 8 14.5 4.5 12 2Z"
              ></path>
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div id="langMenu" class="lang-dropdown">
            <button data-lang="en" class="lang-option">English</button>
            <button data-lang="it" class="lang-option">Italiano</button>
            <button data-lang="fr" class="lang-option">Français</button>
            <button data-lang="ar" class="lang-option">العربية</button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </header>

      <!-- ── Header (lang switcher only) ── -->

      <main>
        <!-- ── Hero ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h1 data-i18n="title_main">Palestinians are Your Eyes</h1>
          </div>
          <div class="opening-quote reveal" data-i18n="opening_quote">
            "Palestinians are your eyes, your tattoo. Palestinians are your
            name, your dreams, your thoughts, and your handkerchief."
          </div>
          <div class="reveal">
            <p data-i18n="intro_para1">
              Six stories, four voices from Gaza. <strong
                >Palestinians are Your Eyes</strong
              > is a project by the Italian-Palestinian company <strong
                >Anqa</strong
              >, bringing to life a collective narrative that knows no borders.
              On October 15, 2026, these stories will resonate in unison during
              a nationwide premiere across Italy and beyond.
            </p>
            <p data-i18n="intro_para2">
              We want these stories to reach every corner of the globe. We
              invite theaters, companies, and artists to become an active part
              of this choral narrative.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── Why October 15th? ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="why_title">Why October 15th?</h2>
            <p data-i18n="why_text">
              October 15th is not just a date on the calendar; it is an open
              wound in our company's history. On that day in 2023, Abraham
              Saidam—a young performer with Anqa—was killed by Israeli
              bombardment. We have chosen this date to honor his memory and
              transform grief into cultural resistance.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── The Stories ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="stories_title">The Stories</h2>
            <p data-i18n="stories_text">
              These are works of fiction interwoven with autobiographical
              elements—diverse narratives that range from raw realism to
              allegorical and symbolic language. The six stories offer a
              "plural" testimony, capturing the tragedy of Gaza from different
              angles, even before the fateful date of October 7, 2023. They are
              interpreted through the "eyes" of young women and men who, in
              their short lives, have known no reality other than one defined by
              war and segregation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── Anqa ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="anqa_title">Anqa: The Story of the Company</h2>
            <p data-i18n="anqa_text1">
              Between late 2022 and early 2023, a group of Italian operators
              from Progetto REC.Palestina traveled to the Gaza Strip to found
              the Anqa Theater Company alongside local youth. Together, they
              created the production <em>All That's Left to Me</em> (a title paraphrasing
              Ghassan Kanafani's <em>All That's Left to You</em>).
            </p>
            <p data-i18n="anqa_text2">
              The play premiered at Ayyam Al Masrah (Theatre Day Productions) in
              Gaza City on January 7, 2023. Inspired by the Odyssey, it served
              as a metaphor for an infinite journey—the painful narrative of
              Palestine, a land where refugees cannot return and from which the
              youth cannot leave.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── A Dream Shattered ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="dream_title">
              A Dream Shattered: The Canceled Tour
            </h2>
            <p data-i18n="dream_text1">
              After a triumphant debut in Gaza City, covered by international
              outlets including Al Jazeera, the project was set for a month-long
              tour in Italy. Stages in Milan, Genoa, Siena, Rome, and Bologna
              were ready to welcome these young actors.
            </p>
            <p data-i18n="dream_text2">
              Everything was ready. Visas were obtained, contracts signed, and
              flights booked. They were scheduled to arrive in Italy on October
              10, 2023. But after October 7, everything changed. In a matter of
              hours, the dream became a nightmare.
            </p>
            <p data-i18n="dream_text3">
              On October 15, 2023—the day rehearsals were to begin in Milan—we
              received the devastating news: Abraham Saidam, who played
              Odysseus, had been killed. Abraham was posthumously awarded the
              "President of the Jury" prize at the 4th Ivo Chiesa International
              Awards by Gad Lerner. The award was accepted by project
              coordinators Simon Pietro De Domenico and Ivan Taverniti, with the
              promise to deliver it to Abraham's father—the sole survivor of the
              massacre—when possible.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── New Project ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="newproject_title">
              The New Project: Palestinians are Your Eyes
            </h2>
            <p data-i18n="newproject_text">
              Following a period of profound despair, the artists of Anqa—both
              Italian and Gazan—realized that the best way to honor Abraham was
              to resist through art. Despite the ongoing bombardment and
              survival-level conditions, they decided to create a new work: a
              cry of desperation that does not block the path to hope. While
              current circumstances prevent these young artists from returning
              to the physical stage, nothing can stop them from entrusting their
              stories to the written word.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── Documentary ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="doc_title">The Documentary Film</h2>
            <p data-i18n="doc_text">
              The impact of Palestinians are Your Eyes will extend beyond the
              stage. Each performance will be recorded to contribute to a
              collective documentary film, gathering emotions and
              interpretations from various stages across the country.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── Conclusion ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <p
              data-i18n="conclusion_text"
              style="font-weight:700; font-size:1.5rem; text-align:center;"
            >
              Theater has always held the power to speak what is often ignored.
              Through Palestinians are Your Eyes, those living a reality usually
              seen only through filtered news fragments can finally be heard.
              This project is more than a play; it is a bridge between worlds
              and an act of civil testimony. The title is taken from a verse by
              the poet Mahmoud Darwish in <em>Lover from Palestine</em>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── How to Participate ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="participate_title">
              How to Participate: October 15, 2026
            </h2>
            <p data-i18n="participate_text">
              To help build this collective memory, we invite theatrical
              institutions, associations, schools, bookstores, and collectives
              to host a performance on October 15, 2026. The project is designed
              for maximum sustainability with minimal technical requirements; it
              can be staged as a simple dramatic reading.
            </p>
            <div class="email-line">
              ✉️ <strong>Email:</strong> progettorec.palestina@gmail.com | CC: s.dedomenico@gmail.com
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <hr class="section-rule" />

        <!-- ── Credits ── -->
        <section class="content-section">
          <div class="reveal">
            <h2 data-i18n="authors_label">
              <strong>Our Tutors & Authors:</strong>
            </h2>

            <div class="credit-block reveal-group">
              <div class="credit-item">
                <span class="credit-author">Ibrahim Alhelou</span>
                <span class="credit-stories">Poesia Madre · Il pedone</span>
              </div>
              <div class="credit-item">
                <span class="credit-author">Dalal Elswerky</span>
                <span class="credit-stories"
                  >Sotto un cielo verde oliva · Un pilastro nel cemento</span
                >
              </div>
              <div class="credit-item">
                <span class="credit-author">Fatma Yousef</span>
                <span class="credit-stories">Prima Lezione</span>
              </div>
              <div class="credit-item">
                <span class="credit-author">Ala'a Sbaiah</span>
                <span class="credit-stories">Anqa Maghrib</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p style="font-weight:500; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
              <strong>Tutors:</strong>
            </p>
            <div class="tutor-block">
              <span class="tutor-item"
                >Simon Pietro De Domenico (Coordinator) .</span
              >
              <span class="tutor-item">Giulia Borghi .</span>
              <span class="tutor-item">Stefania Buraschi .</span>
              <span class="tutor-item">Donato Loiacono .</span>
              <span class="tutor-item">Mattia Majerna .</span>
              <span class="tutor-item">Ivan Taverniti </span>
            </div>

            <!-- <p data-i18n="tutors_text">
              <strong>Tutors:</strong> Simon Pietro De Domenico (Coordinator), Giulia
              Borghi, Stefania Buraschi, Donato Loiacono, Mattia Majerna, Ivan Taverniti.
            </p>
            <p data-i18n="promoted_text">
              <strong>Promoted by:</strong> Progetto REC.Palestina, APS Scighera,
              ACS ONG, VIK CENTER, PEM - HABITAT TEATRALI, and AUDREY ANPI.
            </p> -->
          </div>
        </section>
      </main>

      <footer class="reveal">
        <span data-i18n="footer_text"
          >Palestinians are Your Eyes — collective narrative without borders. ©
          Anqa Theater Company</span
        >
      </footer>
    </div>

